{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_bronte_ver01/data/sn88056094/00295869550/1908012301/0902.xml":{"full_text":"4\nFinancial Panic\nOnly a Case\nof Hysteria.\nBy CHARLES W. MORSE, Flncnclcr and \u2022\u2022Shipping K\u00bbw\u00bb.\n\u2666\u2022\u2666\u2022\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666HE buainesH credit of the country 1ms not been SERI*\nnrsr v imnniwil Confidence must be restored\nC m OCSLY impaired. Confidence must be\n!J! through the very men who first took alarm. When\nX the cry of danger was raised the New York bankers\nACTED LIKE A DROVE OF SHEEP AT THE\nSIGHT OF A STRANGE DOG\u2014one jumped the\nfence, and others followed without stopping to reason out the effect.\nTHE PRESENT SITUATION 13 8IMPLY A CASE OF FINANCIAL\nHYSTERIA, AND WE ALL KNOW THAT HY8TERIC8 ARE SELDOM\nFATAL. WHEN THE BANKERS OF THIS CITY REGAIN CONFI\nDENCE IN THEMSELVE8 AND MEET THE REASONABLE DEMANDS\nOF BUSINESS INTERESTS CONFIDENCE WILL AT ONCE BE RE\nSTORED THROUGHOUT THE COUNTRY.\nStatistics show that there is PLENTY OF MONEY in the banka\nto meet all immediate needs of business. The situation is amazing\nwhen you take these facts into consideration.\nThe bankers of New York are ALONE responsible for whatever\nembarrassment the business men of the city are experiencing. Mat\nters will ease up just as soon as these bankers regain confidence in\nthemselves.\nThe country banks and money lending institutions in the south and\nwest were NEVER IN A MORE PROSPEROUS CONDITION.\nOn account of this there can be no reason to fear a GENERAL panic.\nAlmost every community large enough to support a bank of its own\nhas enough money to tide over its own enterprises.\nI\nj\n\n\n\n\nj\n\ni\nj\nSailing of Our Fleet a\nTurning Point In History.\nBy Confriumin RICHMOND P. HOBSON, th* \"Haro of Santiago.\"\nC HE Japanese are proceeding to organize the Chinese on mili\ntary lines, teaching them in a farrcaching propaganda to\nHATE FOREIGNERS AND PREPARE FOR WAR.\nJapan is furthermore propagating unrest in India, and the\nJapanese victory over Russia HAS SHAKEN THE WHITE\nMAN'S PRESTIGE wherever he is guiding the destinies of men of\nother colors all over the world. The whole trend of events is, there\nfore, toward a contest by the yellow race, AIDED BY THE OTHER\nCOLORED RACES, a struggle to wrost from the white man his\npresent supremacy.\nTHE CONTROL OF THE SEA 18 THE WHITE MAN'S ONLY\nCHANCE FOR MAINTAINING HIS SUPREMACY AND HIS CIVILIZA\nTION AND ALL THAT THE8E MEAN.\nUnfortunately, as the yellow races are uniting the white races are\n\u25a0till DIVIDED. A nation of the white race that controls the ocean\nhas already lent itself to make possible Japanese victory over Russia\nand is now lending itself to make possible JAPANESE VICTORY\nOVER AMERICA.\nWith the sailing of the fleet America becomes the BUFEER for\nthe white man in the struggle for maintaining and perpetuating a civi\nlization that has cost so many centuries of effort and suffering.\nTHE SAILING OF THE FLEET IS AN EVENT OF THE FIRST\nMAGNITUDE AND MARKS A TURNING POINT IN AMERICAN HIS\nTORY AND AN IMPORTANT MEASURE IN THE HISTORY OF THE\nWORLD.\nThe Criminal Class Is Growing.\nBy WILLIAM I. THOMAS, AMlstant Profaasor of Sociology, Unlvaralty\nof Chicago.\nC HE INSANE AND HABITUAL CRIMINAL CLASSES IN AMERICA\nARE INCREASING MORE RAPIDLY THAN THE NORMAL\nPOPULATION. IN THE MORE INTELLIGENT CLASSES THE\nBIRTH RATE 18 LOWER THAN THE DEATH RATE.\nThis, which means RAPID RACE DETERIORATION, makea\ntho question of white or yellow supremacy in the near future a\ngrave one.\nThere are few middle class American families Whose dress and\nmode of living do not represent larger bank accounts than they possess.\nWomen of the upper classes are giving themselves over to personal\nornamentation, STRUGGLES FOR SOCIAL PRE-EMINENCE\nand \"the solemn sacrament of bridge wlxist.\" Child bearing is left\nlargely to the poorer classes.\nThe women of today here in America are rushing into an IN\nTEMPERATE ZONE, and the society of today holds a damning\nbrief against them.\nWe Are Afraid of Hard Work.\nBy Senator REED SMOOT of Utah.\nC UE Americans won't work any more. They are ao busy spec\nulating nnd trying to live off one another that they have\nabandoned labor, and THE FOREIGNER COLLECTS\nTill! WAGES and sends the money abroad.\nIn mv state ami in the surrounding states you CANNOT FIND\nAN AMERICAN LABORER. All the work is performed by for\neigners, mostly Greeks at present, and the moment they get their pay\nthey SHIP EVERY CENT OF IT THAT THEY CAN SPARE\nfrom their bare living expenses to their homes in the old country.\nThat means more G reeks. I do not think that the postal bank, as\n\u2022uggested by Postmaster General Meyer, or any other scheme of gov\nernment guarantee would keep that money from going across the\nocean. If the foreigner is paid more money than he actually needs to\nlive on I1E WILL SEND IT HOME.\nPERHAPS THE FINANCIAL PANIC WILL TEACH US A LESSON\nAND SOME TIME IN THE FUTURE THE AMERICANS WILL GO\nBACK TO WORK. IN THE LAST FEW YEARS OUR PEOPLE HAVE\nBEEN TOO BUSY GAMBLING AND SPECULATING TO DO ANY\nREAL. WORK. THEY HAVE BEEN TOO MUCH ENGAGED IN ROB\nBING ONE ANOTHER.\nI\nj\nA G I R\nFTIs name was John Adolph Jappers.\nJappers was young, tender, fresh- So\nwas bis beard. Jappers had seen about\neighteen years of earthly woe, and he\nwas highly sensitized by nature, al\nthough his father was a bluff old cod\nger without an ounce of nonsense In\nhts whole makeup.\nJohn Jappers fell In love. He bad a\ngirl, at least he thought he had, and he\nthought he had said Interesting things\nand quoted poetry enough to make her\njust crazy to have him propose. One\nday he concluded he would try to see\nhow an offer oT marrlnge, made in\ntrue knightly style, would affect her.\nHe arrayed himself In purple and fine\nlinen, so to speak, made himself look\nas ravlshlngly beautiful as he could\nbe nud sought his divinity.\nCoaxing her Into the parlor, where\nthey might be unobserved, he proceed\ned In due and regular form to offer\nhimself. Did that girl swoon from ex\ncessive gladness? Did Miss Pinky\nBrown fling herself on hts clean shirt\nfront and snivel In ecstasy? Well, not\nto any great extent.\nOn the contrary, she laughed In his\nface and called him a fool; told him to\ngo home nnd ask his mother for a\ngingersnap, and when he seized her by\nthe hand and attempted to remonstrate\nher black and tan terrier seized him\nby the calf of his leg and attempted\nto extract a soup piece from it.\nJappers felt his proud heart break.\nHe wished he had snuff to put In that\ndog's eyes nnd n pistol ball to put be\ntween his own. He waited like a mar\ntyr until that pet of hers had got\nthrough with his lunch, and then, tak\ning his hat, he strode haughtily from\nthe house, resolved to die, to smother\nhis grief In the lethean wave of ob\nlivion.\nLooking nelther*to the right nor left,\nhe made his way to an apothecary's\nstore nnd said he wanted a dose of\narsenic to kill a cat. The druggist had\noften met these crazy looking chaps\nwho wanted to poison cats and ruts\nand things, and, concluding at most\nthat he would only make the cat sick\nof her existence for n few hours, he\nproceeded to put up a strong emetic,\nwith which our heroic youth strode\nhome, fully resolved on a funeral.\nGoing to Ills chnmber, he wrote the\nfollowing note and left it on the ta\nble:\nFriends of This Earth\u2014Fate has frac\ntured my heart. She whom I worshiped\nhas laughed at my love and set her dog\non mo. I pass on. I crave the silent\ntomb. I cannot live in the same world\nwith her and know that I am scorned,\nhave taken arsenic.\nThen he took the emetic. Being\nstrong, It worked hurriedly. It appear\ned to waltz through his troubled In\nterior, and he moaned like a stricken\ncalf. The family rushed up to his\nroom In great alarm. Ills father gruff\nly asked him what the matter was. and\nhe pointed to the paper on the tnble.\nThe old man seized nnd read It.\n\"I'll be hanged if the cussed Idiot\nhasn't been taking arsenic!\" he ex\nclaimed, nnd, seizing his hat. he rush\ned out for tho nearest physician.\nGrabbing a stomach pump, the doc\ntor was soon at the bedside of his\nhowling patient. Then the fun began\nThe parent of thnt poor boy sat upon\nhis stomach, while the doctor applied\nthe pump, nnd the experience thnt he\nunderwent for the next ten minutes\nwas quite enough to make any man\nsigh for \"tho silent tomb.\" He could\nfeel It pull on his very corns.\nAfter nearly turning him Inside out\ntho doctor discovered the real truth\nand limbered up his \"machine\" to go\nhome. That matter of fact father fol\nlowed him to know why he withdrew,\nIf he was quite sure he had pumped\nhim dry, when the doctor Informed\nhim that he hod been made n fool of,\nthat the boy had taken an emetic and\nthat he would take $10 for his troll\nble lu relieving him of It\nThat matter of fact parent paid the\nbill and showed Mr. Medico out of\ndoors, nnd then, with a flood of pa\nI ternal love light In his eyes, he return\nj ed to hts son.\nHo ordered the others from the room,\nnnd, after locking the door, he began\nto act the part of an Indian medicine\nman with the sufferer.\nHe warmed him with a rattan cane.\nHe sat upon him and dusted the most\ndistended portions of his pantaloons\nwith the milm of his hand. He took\nhim by the two legs and, holding him\nup as he would a carcass of mutton,\nho Jounced hts head on the floor sev\neral times.\n\"There!\" said he, after his parental\nlove had spent Itself. \"If I ever catch\nyou making such a confounded mule of\nyourself again I'll cram a pound of nl\ntroglycerln down your throat and\nthrow you out of the window. If you\nwant to die I'll fix you myself, but\ndon't let me see any more suicide In\nthis house.\"\nThen he left that tender youth to hts\nown sad reflections. What they were\nmay be Inferred; but. somehow, he\ndidn't care half so much for Pinky\nBrown as he did before. In fact, he\ndidn't dare to die for fear of his un\nromantte father.\nHe enjoyed about a week of these re\nflections before he could overcome hi*\nphysical weakness sufficiently to get\nout again. But It cured him. and now\nhe has shaved off that springtime mus\ntache. stopped attitudinizing before the\nmirrors and behaves himself quite like\none who came up-through great tribu\nlation\u2014on account of a girl.\nFor an Appetite.\n\"You must have a good appetite,\" re\nmarked the thlu man enviously. \"What\ndo you take for It?\"\n\"In all my experience,\" replied the\nplump one. \"1 have found nothing\nmore suitable than food.\"\u2014 Philadel\nphia Ledger.\nIn Advertising\n\u2014and good business stationery is adver\ntising\u2014it's not so much the taste of the\nman producing the matter, as the consider-,\nation of what will appeal to the class of\npeople he desires to reach. Still, you your\nself will find a keen, personal satisfaction\nin using the crisp, clean sheets of OLD\nHAMPSHIRE BOND. May we show you?\nTHE PRESS PUBLISHING CO.\nTHE PRINT SHOP BY THE LAKE\nBEAT, ESTATE TRANSFERS.\nFollowing is a list of real estate\ntransfers for Kootenai county as tar\nnished by the Panhandle Abstract\ncompany:\nUnited States to heirs of A. L.\nNichols, s hf of nw qr and lot 5, sec\ntion 3 and se qr of ne qr of section\n4, township 48 north, range 4 west..\nE A. Michael to A. J. and J. P.\nMUlsap, s hf of ne qr, section 20,\ntownship 53 north, range 4 west,\n$1500.\nStewart Oman to Washington Wat\ner Power company, se qr of se qr\nand lot 8, section 23, and lots 1 and\n2, section 26, township 48 north,\nrange 3 west, $50\nC. R. Nichols to L. W. Nichols,\nlot 5, and s hf of nw qr of section 3,\nand se qr of ne qr of section 4, town\nship 48 north, range 4 west, $1.\nM. M. Ogden to L. N. Nichols,\nsame as last above.\nC. E. Nichols et al, to L. M. Nich\nols, same as last above.\nL. R. McKinney to H. J. Cadleu,\nlot 5, block 22, O'Brien's Third addi\ntion to Coeur d'Alene, considerat